Hey, i'm working on this embedded C++ project for an automotive sensor module and we're hitting a wall. The system has about 512MB of RAM, but after about 4-6 hours of continuous operation, the heap just completely exhausts and the system crashes. It's not a massive spike, just a very slow, steady climb in usage. 

Here's a simplified snippet of the main loop where we handle the sensor data buffer:

```cpp
void process_sensor_data() {
    uint8_t* buffer = new uint8_t[DATA_PACKET_SIZE];

    if (read_sensor(buffer) == SUCCESS) {
        analyze_packet(buffer);
    }

    // I thought I was handling it here
    // delete[] buffer; 
}

while (system_running) {
    process_sensor_data();
    sleep_ms(10);
}
```

I checked the `analyze_packet` function and it doesn't seem to be taking ownership of the pointer. How can i systematically track down where this leak is happening? Normal Valgrind isn't really an option on this hardware.

